    "rationale": "This example shows the anionic oxy-Cope rearrangement of 3-methyl-1,5-hexadien-3-ol. The substrate is a simple, acyclic 1,5-dien-3-ol, which is the core functional group for this transformation. The reaction, promoted by a base like potassium hydride (KH) and a crown ether, proceeds via a [3,3]-sigmatropic rearrangement of the corresponding potassium alkoxide. The initial product is an enolate, which upon workup (implied) gives the final unsaturated ketone product, hex-5-en-2-one. This is a classic textbook example demonstrating the dramatic rate acceleration and irreversible nature of the anionic variant, which is a key feature of this reaction family.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "The structure is a simple acyclic dienol, avoiding complex ring systems, arenes, or other reactive functional groups that could cause collisions with other named reactions. The core transformation is clearly the [3,3]-sigmatropic rearrangement of a 1,5-dien-3-ol to an unsaturated ketone, which is the defining characteristic of the Oxy-Cope rearrangement. The inclusion of KH and 18-crown-6 specifically points to the anionic variant, which is a major subclass of this family."
  }
}
